Love it:Investors dumped shares of=C2=A0Digital World Acquisition Corp., th=
e blank-check firm set to merge with Donald Trump=E2=80=99s social media co=
mpany, after executives deferred a shareholder vote that was meant to get a=
n extension to complete the deal -- signaling uncertainty surrounding the s=
ponsors=E2=80=99 ability to get enough support.Executives at the special pu=
rpose acquisition company adjourned the meeting to extend the deadline by u=
p to a year until Thursday in an attempt to court retail shareholders to vo=
te, a group that historically misses out on such events. The SPAC needs 65%=
 of shareholders to support the extension.Digital World=E2=80=99s shares fe=
ll as much as 21% to $19.70 on Tuesday, the lowest since the deal was annou=
nced in October, while warrants tied to the firm sank 27%. Its shares had p=
lunged earlier Tuesday after Reuters reported that sponsors don=E2=80=99t e=
xpect to get enough holder support for a one-year extension to complete a d=
eal with Trump Media & Technology Group.Trading volume for both the stock a=
nd warrants were more than ten-times higher than normal as of 12:11 p.m. in=
 New York. More than 3 million shares changed hands as roughly 613,000 warr=
ants were flipped.We  talked about this situation last Thursday. DWAC is sc=
heduled to expire on Sept. 8: If it does not get an extension, then it turn=
s into a pumpkin this Thursday. Then DWAC=E2=80=99s public shareholders get=
 paid out about $10.20 per share in cash,=C2=A0a 2% return on the $10 they =
paid for their shares last September. DWAC=E2=80=99s stock closed on Friday=
 at $24.99. It got as high as $175 last October, after announcing its merge=
r with TMTG. If you own DWAC stock, you think that the prospect=C2=A0of a m=
erger with Trump=E2=80=99s company is worth much, much more than $10.20 per=
 share. You should vote for an extension, to try to make that merger happen=
. It is irrational not to. And yet!=C2=A0Here (from DWAC=E2=80=99s  Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission filings)=C2=A0is a Rumble interview in which a =
musician and worship leader named Chad Nedohin interviewed=C2=A0DWAC Chief =
Executive Officer Patrick Orlando=C2=A0last week:Orlando:=C2=A0Obviously th=
is is an important vote for us. We, we are voting on extending the amount o=
f time that we have to complete this proposed business combination. Current=
ly we were one years back. We=E2=80=99ve had some delays. This is a, a deal=
 with a lot of attention on it. It=E2=80=99s slower than expected, but we=
=E2=80=99re fighting every single day, working every single day to advance =
the ball. And this is where we need the stockholders to come in and have th=
eir votes counted. Typically in proxy votes, the participation of retail sh=
areholders is relatively low. I believe it=E2=80=99s somewhere in the, the =
28% range is once the district that I read, you know, we=E2=80=99re looking=
 for far greater participation. =E2=80=A6So, you know, this is important. I=
t=E2=80=99s, it=E2=80=99s engagement, and exercising your rights is somethi=
ng we really, really stand behind, personally, and you know, I think your a=
ctions, your words, and, your thoughts have to be consistent, and if you fe=
el strongly enough to buy the stock, then, you know, you should be exercisi=
ng your right to vote.Nedohin:=C2=A0And we do feel strongly. This is, uh, t=
his is the DWAC family. We consider ourselves the diamond hands of all diam=
ond hands. This is the team that, that=E2=80=99s gonna go. So, you know wha=
t guys go, DWAC fam. Get those votes in. Uh=E2=80=A6Orlando: Yeah, I mean, =
if you know anybody holding DWAC, that, that isn=E2=80=99t aware of the vot=
e, it=E2=80=99d be really, really important to, to get them aware of the vo=
te. =E2=80=A6Nedohin:=C2=A0Yeah.=C2=A0And so actually, I=E2=80=99m gonna is=
sue a challenge here. Um, to all of the DWAC holders out there, to the DWAC=
 fam, we need 65%,=C2=A0right Patrick?Orlando: Correct.Nedohin: I=E2=80=99m=
 gonna say, guys, let=E2=80=99s go for 90. Let=E2=80=99s show the Deep Stat=
e and the Dems and everybody else out there, all the hedge funds, everybody=
=E2=80=99s gone after this stock. Let=E2=80=99s show them that this is a gr=
oup of retail investors that is engaged and here for the win. Let=E2=80=99s=
 get the 90%. It is your right to vote, and let=E2=80=99s show them that we=
 are going to take that right. Let=E2=80=99s show them what voter turnout l=
ooks like.Look. I am not going to sit here and tell you that it=E2=80=99s r=
ational to pay $24.99 for a share of DWAC stock. I am not at all sure that =
this merger will happen if they get the one-year extension, and if the merg=
er does happen I am not at all sure that Trump Media & Technology Group wil=
l ever make any money for shareholders. But=C2=A0given that DWAC shareholde=
rs apparently think the merger is worth $24.99, it is definitely irrational=
 for them not to vote for the extension. You are definitely better off sell=
ing the stock for $24.99, or $20, or whatever, than you are getting back $1=
0.20 this week. If you are buying DWAC stock today for $20 and then not vot=
ing, you are pretty much throwing away $10. What a weird move.Now, there is=
 another option. Reuters  notes:Were Digital World to fail in its bid to ge=
t its shareholders to back the one-year extension, its management has the r=
ight to extend its life without shareholder approval by up to six months. I=
t is unclear whether Digital World will pursue this option and if it would =
provide enough time for regulators to reach a conclusion on whether to allo=
w the deal to proceed.There is a fun little dynamic here, because DWAC=E2=
=80=99s managers can=C2=A0extend the deadline for six months without shareh=
older approval, but they have to pay for it with their own money. DWAC=E2=
=80=99s sponsors put up about $11.3 million of startup costs to get DWAC ru=
nning. If the deal closes, this will work out very well for them: At Friday=
=E2=80=99s closing price, their stake in DWAC would be worth about $165 mil=
lion.[1] If the deal does not close, they=E2=80=99ll lose their $11 million=
.If they don=E2=80=99t get enough shareholder votes to extend the deadline =
on Thursday, then they will have two choices:=09Return money to shareholder=
s and eat the $11 million loss, or=09Pay another $2,875,000 for a three-mon=
th extension until December, with the possibility of paying another $2,875,=
000 in December for another three-month extension until March 2023.If they =
pay for the extension(s), then they can either close the merger in the next=
 three (or six) months, or they can try again to get enough shareholder vot=
es for a longer extension. But then they=E2=80=99ve got more money committe=
d: Instead of the $11 million they put up originally, they=E2=80=99ll have =
$14 million or $17 million committed to this thing. If the merger closes, t=
hey get that money back or can convert it into shares, which makes this an =
even better deal for them. But if the merger does not close, that money goe=
s to the public shareholders; the sponsors don=E2=80=99t get it back.[2]Obv=
iously if they close the merger and get $165 million worth of stock then th=
e extra $3 million they have to put in now is pocket change. You=E2=80=99re=
 betting $3 million to win $165 million, come on. On the other hand if they=
 think that the odds of closing the deal are really really really really re=
ally low, then that=E2=80=99s throwing good money after bad.What do=C2=A0yo=
u=C2=A0think the odds are of this deal closing? Are they better than 1 in 5=
0? What do you think DWAC=E2=80=99s sponsors think the odds are? When DWAC =
initially went public it said that it would give notice of any paid-for ext=
ension at least three days before its deadline, and it=E2=80=99s now two da=
ys before the deadline and there=E2=80=99s been no notice.[3] I=E2=80=99m n=
ot sure if that means anything;=C2=A0DWAC is=C2=A0not necessarily a stickle=
r for proper procedures,=C2=A0and anyway if they pay for the extension at t=
he last minute no one will complain too much. Still. They don=E2=80=99t exa=
ctly seem confident.
