      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Another high-stakes meeting  is happening today:A hearing in the legal batt=
le between Elon Musk and Twitter Inc. is scheduled Tuesday afternoon in Del=
aware Chancery Court for oral arguments over a range of issues, including M=
r. Musk=E2=80=99s request to amend his countersuit.Chancellor Kathaleen McC=
ormick said in a filing Friday she will consider several pending legal moti=
ons from both parties, such as Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s recent request to add all=
egations from a whistleblower complaint by Twitter=E2=80=99s former head of=
 security, Peiter Zatko, to his counterclaims.Mr. Musk has also requested t=
hat the five-day nonjury trial be pushed to November from October.The heari=
ng is scheduled to start at 1:30 p.m. ET and each side will be permitted 90=
 minutes to present arguments. The judge said they would begin with the so-=
called discovery motions, over each side=E2=80=99s various requests for inf=
ormation, before moving to Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s request to amend his complain=
t.I don=E2=80=99t know how this will go. I suppose the main options are:=09=
Chancellor McCormick denies Musk=E2=80=99s request to amend his complaint a=
nd the trial goes ahead as scheduled, on the fairly narrow issue of whether=
 Twitter was lying about how it counts bot accounts; or=09She grants Musk=
=E2=80=99s request to amend his complaint, and probably delays the trial a =
bit, and Musk gets to  throw lots of new claims at Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
bout its alleged bad security practices, compliance failures, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0to see if any of them stick.The second option seems very annoying,=
 and bad for Twitter. It would mean that Twitter has to defend on lots more=
 fronts. =E2=80=9CMusk is good at muddying waters and impressing the impres=
sionable,=E2=80=9D  I once wrote about this case,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand this wo=
uld play to his strengths.=E2=80=9D It would mean that the trial is delayed=
 and there=E2=80=99s more risk of the deal falling apart even if Twitter wi=
ns. And it would perhaps=C2=A0mean that Chancellor McCormick sees something=
 in Musk=E2=80=99s claims, that she might believe that he=E2=80=99s serious=
 when he says that Twitter has been running a comprehensive fraud designed =
to trick him into buying it, rather than just being a whimsical rich guy tr=
ying to get out of a deal because he overpaid.The first option is good for =
Twitter in some ways: It means that she=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t take Musk part=
icularly seriously as he alleges assorted frauds, and just wants to hold hi=
m to (his first claimed set of reasons for getting out of) his deal. But it=
=E2=80=99s a mess. What if the whistle-blower complaint is entirely true? W=
hat if you put the worst possible spin on it?=C2=A0What if Twitter=C2=A0has=
=C2=A0been doing a bunch of miscellaneous fraud? It=E2=80=99s  hardly fair =
to make Elon Musk buy the company anyway. If he gets to amend his complaint=
, then he has to litigate all of it, all at once, in Delaware, in a sophist=
icated court that is used to high-stakes merger disputes, in front of a jud=
ge who has a record of being skeptical of buyers trying to get out of deals=
 because they overpaid. If he doesn=E2=80=99t, then he=E2=80=99s going to a=
ppeal, and maybe he=E2=80=99ll sue in other courts, and the whole thing is =
going to become muddier and more convoluted.=C2=A0
