      Stablecoins
   =20
 =20
Here is a bad way for a stock exchange to work:=09I link my bank account, a=
t Chase Bank, to my stock-exchange account.=09I go to the stock exchange an=
d bid $100=C2=A0for a share of XYZ stock.=09My bid goes onto the stock exch=
ange=E2=80=99s order book as =E2=80=9C100 Chase dollars for XYZ.=E2=80=9D=
=09You come=C2=A0to the exchange and offer=C2=A0to sell XYZ stock at $100 p=
er share, but you demand to be paid from an account at Citibank.=09Your off=
er goes onto the stock exchange=E2=80=99s order book as =E2=80=9CXYZ for 10=
0 Citi dollars.=E2=80=9D=09Because my bid is in Chase dollars and your offe=
r is for Citi dollars, our orders are not matched with each other.=09We do =
not trade.That=C2=A0is dumb. That is not how the stock exchange works. It=
=C2=A0could=C2=A0work that way. There=C2=A0are=C2=A0financial markets where=
 your bank is relevant, I guess,[4] and I suppose in the olden days buying =
stock with a check drawn on a good upstanding bank would be a different tra=
de from buying stock with a check drawn on a faraway wildcat bank. And of c=
ourse the actual processes of connecting to an exchange and settling trades=
 involve credit evaluations, and if you tried to connect directly to the Ne=
w York Stock Exchange and post millions of dollars of bids and offers using=
 your account at the Bank of Magic Beans then the NYSE would have questions=
. And of course if you have Swiss francs and want to buy US stocks, or you =
have US dollars and want to buy Swiss stocks, you will need to do some conv=
erting. But generally speaking the structure of the stock exchange is about=
 trading stocks for dollars. The stocks are all different but the dollars a=
re all the same.In cryptocurrency markets, broadly, people like to exchange=
 volatile cryptocurrencies (Bitcoin, Ether, etc.) for dollars, but they are=
 particular about what flavor of dollars they want. Some traders will want =
to send out Bitcoin and get back actual U.S. dollars in their bank accounts=
. Most professional crypto traders do not, for various ease-of-settlement, =
staying-in-the-crypto-system and/or regulatory reasons. They prefer to get =
paid in stablecoins, dollar-denominated tokens that live natively on some c=
rypto blockchain. They will sell you Bitcoin and get back Circle=E2=80=99s =
USDC or Binance=E2=80=99s BUSD or Tether=E2=80=99s USDT or some other dolla=
r stablecoin.This creates the annoying practical difficulty that crypto exc=
hanges will list trading pairs like =E2=80=9CBitcoin/USDC=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9CBitcoin/USDT,=E2=80=9D and if you want to trade a Bitcoin for dollars=
 you will have to choose which flavor of dollar you want. And the liquidity=
 will be divided: Some people will bid=C2=A0one flavor of dollars for Bitco=
in, and other people will bid another flavor of dollars; some people will o=
ffer to sell Bitcoin for one flavor of dollars, while others will offer Bit=
coin for a different flavor. And the people who bid USDC will not trade wit=
h the people who offer for USDT.And sometimes there is some reason for this=
: Someone  won=E2=80=99t trust Tether, or won=E2=80=99t be able to  get USD=
C, or whatever. Often, though, everyone is more or less indifferent between=
 flavors of dollars; they just want to trade Bitcoin for dollar-ish things =
or dollar-ish things for Bitcoin. But because there are different flavors o=
f dollar in the crypto world, the liquidity is fragmented.Anyway:Binance, t=
he largest crypto exchange by volume, will start converting any existing us=
er balances and new deposits of USD Coin (USDC), Pax Dollar (USDP) and True=
 USD (TUSD) into the company=E2=80=99s own stablecoin, according to=C2=A0a =
statement published on Monday. The conversion is scheduled to begin Sept. 2=
9.=C2=A0USDC, issued by=C2=A0Circle Internet Financial, is the second-ranke=
d stablecoin after Tether=E2=80=99s USDT, with a market value of nearly $52=
 billion, according to data from CoinGecko. Binance=E2=80=99s stablecoin, B=
USD, is a distant third at around $19.3 billion.=C2=A0The exchange said the=
 move is intended =E2=80=9Cto enhance liquidity and capital-efficiency for =
users.=E2=80=9D Binance will also remove and stop any trading on spot pairs=
 that involve USDC, USDP or TUSD, the exchange said in the statement.=C2=A0=
Now most of Binance=E2=80=99s dollar-denominated trading will=C2=A0be for B=
inance=E2=80=99s flavor of dollars, rather than being for several different=
 flavors.=C2=A0Evgeny Gaevoy  tweeted: =E2=80=9CRemoving most stablecoin pa=
irs is a good thing - liquidity doesn=E2=80=99t have to be split between mu=
ltiple stablecoins, making market makers=E2=80=99 job easier and markets ov=
erall more liquid.=E2=80=9D And then if you are a market maker and you get =
Binance-flavored dollars, you can pretty easily turn them into Coinbase-fla=
vored dollars (USDC) to trade on Coinbase, or various other flavors of doll=
ars to trade elsewhere.=C2=A0I suppose that if you=E2=80=99re a big crypto =
market maker you might still have to post, like, Bitcoin/BUSD markets on Bi=
nance and Bitcoin/USDC markets on Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0just as stock mar=
ket makers need to post, like, Tesla/dollar markets on all of the various U=
S stock exchanges. There is still some fragmentation, and each of your mark=
ets is in a slightly different currency. Still I guess it is more efficient=
 to have one currency per exchange.
