      ESG Cyber
   =20
 =20
=E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D is an odd combination. ESG investing involves looking=
 at the environmental, social and governance characteristics of an investme=
nt. Why those three things? Why=C2=A0governance? We have  talked=C2=A0recen=
tly about different ways to think about ESG investing. Two important ones a=
re[5]:=09You just want to make money, you worry about the risks that enviro=
nmental and social problems pose to the future cash flows of companies, so =
you buy ESG funds that take into account those risks to buy stocks that wil=
l perform well in the long term.=09You want to make the world better with y=
our investing, you worry about environmental and social problems, so you bu=
y ESG funds that try to solve those problems by allocating capital to envir=
onmentally sound companies or by telling corporate managers not to be racis=
t or whatever.Fine, two different though overlapping ways to look at enviro=
nmental and social investing. But apply that to corporate governance, the G=
 in ESG:=09You just want to make money, so you buy stocks in companies with=
 sound corporate-governance practices that align the interests of executive=
s and shareholders. These companies, you expect, will pursue shareholder va=
lue more efficiently: The managers are more directly answerable to sharehol=
ders, so they will focus more on making money and less on their own interes=
ts.=09You want to make the world =E2=80=A6=C2=A0better =E2=80=A6=C2=A0for =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0shareholders? You want to get rid of staggered boards and ta=
keover protections, so that companies are more answerable to shareholders? =
So that they are more responsive to activists who demand stock buybacks? So=
 that they are more vulnerable to hostile takeovers? So that their executiv=
es don=E2=80=99t have cushy jobs that can be done lazily, but have to inste=
ad constantly push to make more money?It=E2=80=99s weird. In some ways =E2=
=80=9Cgovernance=E2=80=9D is the opposite of =E2=80=9Cenvironmental and soc=
ial.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CGovernance=E2=80=9D is about making managers answera=
ble to shareholders, and shareholders have, historically, cared mostly abou=
t profits. That of course has changed, and I suppose now good governance me=
ans that the managers will care about shareholders=E2=80=99 environmental a=
nd social concerns.Still, I think it is hard to have a touchy-feely, social=
ly-responsible, make-the-world-better approach to=C2=A0governance=C2=A0fact=
ors. If you care about corporate governance, it is because you want to impr=
ove the performance of the companies in your portfolio.[6]But how is that d=
ifferent from regular old active management? What is the difference between=
 saying =E2=80=9CI will buy companies whose managers have a good track reco=
rd=C2=A0of growing sales=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CI will buy companies whose m=
anagers have a good track record of listening to shareholders=E2=80=9D? Wha=
t makes the latter ESG and the former just, you know, regular? I think two =
plausible answers are:=09=E2=80=9CGovernance=E2=80=9D is just a relatively =
newer thing for people to care about, so it is a relatively nontraditional =
investment factor, so people lump it with other non-traditional =E2=80=9CES=
G=E2=80=9D factors.=C2=A0=09Governance is a=C2=A0systemic=C2=A0sort of risk=
: Every company grows sales in a different way, but every takeover protecti=
on is bad in the same way. If you are a giant diversified quasi-index inves=
tor, you don=E2=80=99t have the expertise or time to call up the managers o=
f your hundreds of investments and tell them how to grow their sales. But y=
ou can vote against staggered boards at all of those companies. If you are =
big and diversified enough, you have to care about systemic factors =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0climate change, social unrest and, sure,=C2=A0governance best prac=
tices=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0rather than specifics.On this rough framework, an=
ything that is (1) new-ish and (2) applicable to lots of companies could mo=
re or less count as ESG? Like, if you are worried that lots of companies ha=
ve bad cybersecurity, and that if they get hacked their stock prices will g=
o down, is that ESG?  Sure why not:Lombard Odier Investment Managers said t=
he =E2=80=9Cshocking=E2=80=9D results of an analysis into cybersecurity ris=
ks lurking in portfolio companies has led it to apply ESG processes far mor=
e broadly to protect its funds from losses.The Swiss asset manager is now o=
n a campaign =E2=80=9Cto push these companies to get their basic cyber hygi=
ene in order,=E2=80=9D said Jeroen van Oerle, portfolio manager of Lombard =
Odier=E2=80=99s Global FinTech fund. The firm wants to treat =E2=80=9Ccyber=
security risks the same way as we look at climate-related risks, or water u=
sage risks, or corporate governance risks,=E2=80=9D he said.Since the summe=
r, Lombard Odier has been screening more than 500 companies each month in a=
n effort to detect software vulnerabilities. The analysis found that about =
20% are running outdated software. =E2=80=9CTo me, that was shocking,=E2=80=
=9D van Oerle said. ...Researchers at Berenberg recently identified cyberse=
curity as a key ESG theme for 2022, while analysts at Goldman Sachs Group I=
nc. have singled out cyberattacks as an area of particular concern to ESG i=
nvestors.Van Oerle said he=E2=80=99s ready to sell shares of a company if h=
e=E2=80=99s left with the impression that management isn=E2=80=99t doing en=
ough to protect the business from cybersecurity risks.=C2=A0Yeah I mean =E2=
=80=9CI am willing to sell shares of a company if I have the impression tha=
t the managers are not doing enough to protect against large near-term fina=
ncial risk=E2=80=9D seems like a pretty normal position that you could have=
 had a decade ago without calling it ESG? But it=E2=80=99s ESG enough I gue=
ss.Meanwhile in the US, Republican politicians are trying to  ban ESG inves=
ting. What does that mean for cybersecurity? If you are an investment manag=
er and you avoid companies that are bad at information security, is that il=
legal?
