5px;">DWAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/28964827.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDYvdHJ1bXAtdGllZC1zcGFjLXNpbmtzLW9uLWNvbmNlcm5zLWF=
ib3V0LWNvbXBsZXRpb24tb2YtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbW=
VkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MDYmdXRtX2Nhb=
XBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB88c2c2d3" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Love it</=
a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors dumped shares of=
=C2=A0Digital World Acquisition Corp., the blank-check firm set to merge wi=
th Donald Trump=E2=80=99s social media company, after executives deferred a=
 shareholder vote that was meant to get an extension to complete the deal -=
- signaling uncertainty surrounding the sponsors=E2=80=99 ability to get en=
ough support.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Executives at the special pur=
pose acquisition company adjourned the meeting to extend the deadline by up=
 to a year until Thursday in an attempt to court retail shareholders to vot=
e, a group that historically misses out on such events. The SPAC needs 65% =
of shareholders to support the extension.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">D=
igital World=E2=80=99s shares fell as much as 21% to $19.70 on Tuesday, the=
 lowest since the deal was announced in October, while warrants tied to the=
 firm sank 27%. Its shares had plunged earlier Tuesday after Reuters report=
ed that sponsors don=E2=80=99t expect to get enough holder support for a on=
e-year extension to complete a deal with Trump Media &amp; Technology Group=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading volume for both the stock and war=
rants were more than ten-times higher than normal as of 12:11 p.m. in New Y=
ork. More than 3 million shares changed hands as roughly 613,000 warrants w=
ere flipped.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28964827.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDEvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWM=
tbmVlZHMtbW9yZS10aW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb53f3d8b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about</a> =
this situation last Thursday. DWAC is scheduled to expire on Sept. 8: If it=
 does not get an extension, then it turns into a pumpkin this Thursday. The=
n DWAC=E2=80=99s public shareholders get paid out about $10.20 per share in=
 cash,=C2=A0a 2% return on the $10 they paid for their shares last Septembe=
r. DWAC=E2=80=99s stock closed on Friday at $24.99. It got as high as $175 =
last October, after announcing its merger with TMTG. If you own DWAC stock,=
 you think that the prospect=C2=A0of a merger with Trump=E2=80=99s company =
is worth much, much more than $10.20 per share. You should vote for an exte=
nsion, to try to make that merger happen. It is irrational not to. And yet!=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here (from DWAC=E2=80=99s <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28964827.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2MzUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjM2OTg=
0L2QzOTgxODNkZGVmYTE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3803bc28" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Se=
curities and Exchange Commission filings</a>)=C2=A0is a Rumble interview in=
 which a musician and worship leader named Chad Nedohin interviewed=C2=A0DW=
AC Chief Executive Officer Patrick Orlando=C2=A0last week:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Orlando:</strong>=C2=A0Obviously this i=
s an important vote for us. We, we are voting on extending the amount of ti=
me that we have to complete this proposed business combination. Currently w=
e were one years back. We=E2=80=99ve had some delays. This is a, a deal wit=
h a lot of attention on it. It=E2=80=99s slower than expected, but we=E2=80=
=99re fighting every single day, working every single day to advance the ba=
ll. And this is where we need the stockholders to come in and have their vo=
tes counted. Typically in proxy votes, the participation of retail sharehol=
ders is relatively low. I believe it=E2=80=99s somewhere in the, the 28% ra=
nge is once the district that I read, you know, we=E2=80=99re looking for f=
ar greater participation. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, you=
 know, this is important. It=E2=80=99s, it=E2=80=99s engagement, and exerci=
sing your rights is something we really, really stand behind, personally, a=
nd you know, I think your actions, your words, and, your thoughts have to b=
e consistent, and if you feel strongly enough to buy the stock, then, you k=
now, you should be exercising your right to vote.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;"><strong>Nedohin:</strong>=C2=A0And we do feel strongly. This is, uh,=
 this is the DWAC family. We consider ourselves the diamond hands of all di=
amond hands. This is the team that, that=E2=80=99s gonna go. So, you know w=
hat guys go, DWAC fam. Get those votes in. Uh=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;"><strong>Orlando:</strong> Yeah, I mean, if you know anybody hol=
ding DWAC, that, that isn=E2=80=99t aware of the vote, it=E2=80=99d be real=
ly, really important to, to get them aware of the vote. =E2=80=A6</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Nedohin:</strong>=C2=A0Yeah.=C2=A0And so act=
ually, I=E2=80=99m gonna issue a challenge here. Um, to all of the DWAC hol=
ders out there, to the DWAC fam, we need 65%,=C2=A0right Patrick?</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Orlando:</strong> Correct.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;"><strong>Nedohin: </strong>I=E2=80=99m gonna say, guys, let=
=E2=80=99s go for 90. Let=E2=80=99s show the Deep State and the Dems and ev=
erybody else out there, all the hedge funds, everybody=E2=80=99s gone after=
 this stock. Let=E2=80=99s show them that this is a group of retail investo=
rs that is engaged and here for the win. Let=E2=80=99s get the 90%. It is y=
our right to vote, and let=E2=80=99s show them that we are going to take th=
at right. Let=E2=80=99s show them what voter turnout looks like.</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look. I am not going to sit here and tel=
l you that it=E2=80=99s rational to pay $24.99 for a share of DWAC stock. I=
 am not at all sure that this merger will happen if they get the one-year e=
xtension, and if the merger does happen I am not at all sure that Trump Med=
ia &amp; Technology Group will ever make any money for shareholders. But=C2=
=A0given that DWAC shareholders apparently think the merger is worth $24.99=
, it is definitely irrational for them not to vote for the extension. You a=
re definitely better off selling the stock for $24.99, or $20, or whatever,=
 than you are getting back $10.20 this week. If you are buying DWAC stock t=
oday for $20 and then not voting, you are pretty much throwing away $10. Wh=
at a weird move.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, there is another opti=
on. Reuters <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/289648=
27.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vbWFya2V0cy9kZWFscy9leGNsdXNpdmUtZ=
GVhbC1wYXJ0bmVyLXRydW1wcy10cnV0aC1zb2NpYWwtZmFpbHMtZ2V0LWJhY2tpbmctc3BhYy1l=
eHRlbnNpb24tMjAyMi0wOS0wNi8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB038ab251" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not=
es</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Were Digital World to f=
ail in its bid to get its shareholders to back the one-year extension, its =
management has the right to extend its life without shareholder approval by=
 up to six months. It is unclear whether Digital World will pursue this opt=
ion and if it would provide enough time for regulators to reach a conclusio=
n on whether to allow the deal to proceed.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">There is a fun little dynamic here, because DWAC=E2=80=99s man=
agers <em>can=C2=A0</em>extend the deadline for six months without sharehol=
der approval, but they have to pay for it with their own money. DWAC=E2=80=
=99s sponsors put up about $11.3 million of startup costs to get DWAC runni=
ng. If the deal closes, this will work out very well for them: At Friday=E2=
=80=99s closing price, their stake in DWAC would be worth about $165 millio=
n.[1] If the deal does not close, they=E2=80=99ll lose their $11 million.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If they don=E2=80=99t get enough shareholder=
 votes to extend the deadline on Thursday, then they will have two choices:=
</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px=
 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Return money to shareholders and =
eat the $11 million loss, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Pay a=
nother $2,875,000 for a three-month extension until December, with the poss=
ibility of paying another $2,875,000 in December for another three-month ex=
tension until March 2023.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If they pay=
 for the extension(s), then they can either close the merger in the next th=
ree (or six) months, or they can try again to get enough shareholder votes =
for a longer extension. But then they=E2=80=99ve got more money committed: =
Instead of the $11 million they put up originally, they=E2=80=99ll have $14=
 million or $17 million committed to this thing. If the merger closes, they=
 get that money back or can convert it into shares, which makes this an eve=
n better deal for them. But if the merger does not close, that money goes t=
o the public shareholders; the sponsors don=E2=80=99t get it back.[2]</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously if they close the merger and get $165 =
million worth of stock then the extra $3 million they have to put in now is=
 pocket change. You=E2=80=99re betting $3 million to win $165 million, come=
 on. On the other hand if they think that the odds of closing the deal are =
really really really really really low, then that=E2=80=99s throwing good m=
oney after bad.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0<=
/em>think the odds are of this deal closing? Are they better than 1 in 50? =
What do you think DWAC=E2=80=99s sponsors think the odds are? When DWAC ini=
tially went public it said that it would give notice of any paid-for extens=
ion at least three days before its deadline, and it=E2=80=99s now two days =
before the deadline and there=E2=80=99s been no notice.[3] I=E2=80=99m not =
sure if that means anything;=C2=A0DWAC is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28964827.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjcvZGlnaXRhbC13b3JsZC1kaXNjbG9zZXMtZ3Jhb=
mQtanVyeS1pbi1uZXcteW9yay13YW50cy1pbmZvcm1hdGlvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTA2MjJfTU9O=
RVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0=
yMjA5MDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8ef6d7a3"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">not necessarily a stickler for proper procedures</a>,=C2=A0and any=
way if they pay for the extension at the last minute no one will complain t=
oo much. Still. They don=E2=80=99t exactly seem confident.</p><table class=
