</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a bad way for a stock exchange=
 to work:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; mar=
gin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I link my bank account, =
at Chase Bank, to my stock-exchange account.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">I go to the stock exchange and bid $100=C2=A0for a share of XYZ =
stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">My bid goes onto the stock =
exchange=E2=80=99s order book as =E2=80=9C100 Chase dollars for XYZ.=E2=80=
=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You come=C2=A0to the exchange =
and offer=C2=A0to sell XYZ stock at $100 per share, but you demand to be pa=
id from an account at Citibank.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yo=
ur offer goes onto the stock exchange=E2=80=99s order book as =E2=80=9CXYZ =
for 100 Citi dollars.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bec=
ause my bid is in Chase dollars and your offer is for Citi dollars, our ord=
ers are not matched with each other.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">We do not trade.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=C2=A0is dumb=
. That is not how the stock exchange works. It=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>wor=
k that way. There=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>financial markets where your bank =
is relevant, I guess,[4] and I suppose in the olden days buying stock with =
a check drawn on a good upstanding bank would be a different trade from buy=
ing stock with a check drawn on a faraway wildcat bank. And of course the a=
ctual processes of connecting to an exchange and settling trades involve cr=
edit evaluations, and if you tried to connect directly to the New York Stoc=
k Exchange and post millions of dollars of bids and offers using your accou=
nt at the Bank of Magic Beans then the NYSE would have questions. And of co=
urse if you have Swiss francs and want to buy US stocks, or you have US dol=
lars and want to buy Swiss stocks, you will need to do some converting. But=
 generally speaking the structure of the stock exchange is about trading st=
ocks for dollars. The stocks are all different but the dollars are all the =
same.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In cryptocurrency markets, broadly, p=
eople like to exchange volatile cryptocurrencies (Bitcoin, Ether, etc.) for=
 dollars, but they are particular about what flavor of dollars they want. S=
ome traders will want to send out Bitcoin and get back actual U.S. dollars =
in their bank accounts. Most professional crypto traders do not, for variou=
s ease-of-settlement, staying-in-the-crypto-system and/or regulatory reason=
s. They prefer to get paid in stablecoins, dollar-denominated tokens that l=
ive natively on some crypto blockchain. They will sell you Bitcoin and get =
back Circle=E2=80=99s USDC or Binance=E2=80=99s BUSD or Tether=E2=80=99s US=
DT or some other dollar stablecoin.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This cr=
eates the annoying practical difficulty that crypto exchanges will list tra=
ding pairs like =E2=80=9CBitcoin/USDC=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CBitcoin/USDT,=
=E2=80=9D and if you want to trade a Bitcoin for dollars you will have to c=
hoose which flavor of dollar you want. And the liquidity will be divided: S=
ome people will bid=C2=A0one flavor of dollars for Bitcoin, and other peopl=
e will bid another flavor of dollars; some people will offer to sell Bitcoi=
n for one flavor of dollars, while others will offer Bitcoin for a differen=
t flavor. And the people who bid USDC will not trade with the people who of=
fer for USDT.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And sometimes there is some r=
eason for this: Someone <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/28964827.283552/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1sb29raW5nLWZvci10ZXRo=
