width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> talked=C2=A0recently</a> about different ways to think=
 about ESG investing. Two important ones are[5]:</p><ol style=3D"list-style=
-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">You just want to make money, you worry about the risks that =
environmental and social problems pose to the future cash flows of companie=
s, so you buy ESG funds that take into account those risks to buy stocks th=
at will perform well in the long term.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">You want to make the world better with your investing, you worry about=
 environmental and social problems, so you buy ESG funds that try to solve =
those problems by allocating capital to environmentally sound companies or =
by telling corporate managers not to be racist or whatever.</li></ol><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine, two different though overlapping ways to look =
at environmental and social investing. But apply that to corporate governan=
ce, the G in ESG:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 4=
0px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You just want to=
 make money, so you buy stocks in companies with sound corporate-governance=
 practices that align the interests of executives and shareholders. These c=
ompanies, you expect, will pursue shareholder value more efficiently: The m=
anagers are more directly answerable to shareholders, so they will focus mo=
re on making money and less on their own interests.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">You want to make the world =E2=80=A6=C2=A0better =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0for =E2=80=A6=C2=A0shareholders? You want to get rid of staggered =
boards and takeover protections, so that companies are more answerable to s=
hareholders? So that they are more responsive to activists who demand stock=
 buybacks? So that they are more vulnerable to hostile takeovers? So that t=
heir executives don=E2=80=99t have cushy jobs that can be done lazily, but =
have to instead constantly push to make more money?</li></ol><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s weird. In some ways =E2=80=9Cgovernance=E2=80=
=9D is the opposite of =E2=80=9Cenvironmental and social.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=9CGovernance=E2=80=9D is about making managers answerable to shareholders,=
 and shareholders have, historically, cared mostly about profits. That of c=
ourse has changed, and I suppose now good governance means that the manager=
s will care about shareholders=E2=80=99 environmental and social concerns.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, I think it is hard to have a touchy-=
feely, socially-responsible, make-the-world-better approach to=C2=A0<em>gov=
ernance=C2=A0</em>factors. If you care about corporate governance, it is be=
cause you want to improve the performance of the companies in your portfoli=
o.[6]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But how is that different from regula=
r old active management? What is the difference between saying =E2=80=9CI w=
ill buy companies whose managers have a good track record=C2=A0of growing s=
ales=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CI will buy companies whose managers have a good =
track record of listening to shareholders=E2=80=9D? What makes the latter E=
SG and the former just, you know, regular? I think two plausible answers ar=
e:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16=
px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CGovernance=E2=80=9D is=
 just a relatively newer thing for people to care about, so it is a relativ=
ely nontraditional investment factor, so people lump it with other non-trad=
itional =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D factors.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">Governance is a=C2=A0<em>systemic=C2=A0</em>sort of risk: Every =
company grows sales in a different way, but every takeover protection is ba=
